# Phase 2 Architecture

## Purpose
This document freezes the main electrical architecture of Version 1 before schematic capture begins. It defines how the 8×8×8 monochrome LED cube will be powered, controlled, and multiplexed, so later schematic and PCB work can follow a fixed plan.

## Version 1 summary
Version 1 is an 8×8×8 monochrome LED cube driven by an ESP32. The cube uses multiplexed scanning with one active layer at a time. Power enters through USB-C at 5 V. The controller PCB contains the USB-C 5 V input stage, 5 V power distribution, LED-driving logic, layer-switching circuitry, and the ESP32 interface. Firmware is included and will provide preloaded animations, serial debug, and a button-based animation switch function.

## Frozen architecture decisions

### Display type
- 8×8×8 monochrome LED cube
- total LEDs: 512
- one controller PCB for the first version

### Main controller
- ESP32
- responsible for refresh timing, animation playback, input handling, and serial debug output

### Scanning method
- multiplexed display
- one layer active at a time
- 8 layers total
- 64 column signals active within the selected layer

### Layer switching topology
- low-side layer switching
- cube arranged as common-cathode layers
- each layer cathode is switched to ground by a dedicated MOSFET
- the layer MOSFET gates are controlled through one section of the driver chain rather than directly from ESP32 GPIO

### Column driving method
- column lines provide the sourcing path for LED current
- 64 column outputs are generated through a serially controlled driver chain rather than direct ESP32 GPIO control
- current limiting is placed in the column paths
- the same serial driver chain architecture also provides control bits for the layer-switching MOSFETs

### Power input method
- USB-C used as 5 V power input
- the ESP32 is powered from 5 V through the regulator already present on the selected ESP32 board or module carrier
- no separate external 5 V to 3.3 V regulator is required on the controller PCB unless later hardware selection proves otherwise
- LED drive remains on the 5 V rail

### User input
- one button is included to switch between preloaded animations
- the button is read by the ESP32
- the button interface is intended for simple local control, not for a full menu system

### Firmware scope
- included in Version 1
- supports preloaded animations
- supports serial debug
- supports button-based animation switching
- no advanced external control interface in Version 1

## High-level functional description
The ESP32 controls the cube through two main sections: the column drive chain and the layer switching stage. The column drive chain determines which LEDs within the currently selected layer should light. A dedicated part of that same driver chain also controls which layer MOSFET is enabled. The active layer MOSFET connects one layer cathode plane to ground. By rapidly stepping through the layers and updating the driver data, the firmware creates the appearance of a full 3D image.

A single user button provides local control for changing the currently active animation. The button is connected to the ESP32 and handled in firmware.

Power enters the board from USB-C as 5 V. The 5 V rail feeds the LED-driving section directly and also feeds the ESP32 through its onboard 5 V to 3.3 V conversion path. The ESP32 generates the timing and data needed to keep the display refreshed while also running the animation logic.

## Chosen layer switching approach

### Decision
Version 1 uses low-side switching for the 8 layers, implemented with MOSFETs.

### Meaning
Each layer is a common-cathode plane. A layer turns on when its cathode plane is connected to ground through its switching MOSFET. Only one layer is enabled at a time during normal refresh operation.

### Why this was chosen
- simpler than high-side switching
- easy to combine with a common-cathode layer arrangement
- good fit for a first student PCB
- practical for multiplexed scanning
- easy to reason about during bring-up and debugging

### Additional control decision
The layer MOSFETs are not driven directly by separate ESP32 pins. Instead, their control signals are generated by one section of the serial driver chain. This keeps the control structure centralized and reduces direct GPIO usage on the ESP32.

### Design consequences
- column drivers must source current into LEDs
- each layer MOSFET must sink the full current of one active layer
- the driver chain must provide not only column data but also layer-select control
- timing of column updates and layer selection must be coordinated carefully
- ground return paths for layer current must be short and low impedance
- MOSFET choice must be based on worst-case active-layer current, not average current

## Chosen driver-chain approach

### Decision
The display uses a serially loaded driver chain controlled by the ESP32.

### Functions of the driver chain
The driver chain is responsible for:
- generating the 64 column control outputs
- providing the control outputs used to select the active layer MOSFET
- reducing the number of direct control pins required from the ESP32

### Why this was chosen
- avoids using a large number of direct GPIO pins
- keeps the ESP32 pin budget practical
- makes the architecture easy to document
- reduces routing complexity compared with a wide direct-parallel interface
- creates one consistent control path for both columns and layer selection

### Design consequences
- firmware must shift and latch driver data reliably
- column data and layer-select data must be packed and updated in the correct order
- blanking during layer changes may be needed to prevent ghosting
- the driver outputs used for MOSFET control must be electrically suitable for the gate-drive scheme
- the full driver chain timing must be considered as one refresh system, not as separate column and layer blocks

## Current-limiting strategy

### Decision
Current limiting will be implemented in the column paths.

### Reason
This keeps the current setting associated with each driven column line and gives a clear, repeatable approach for a multiplexed display architecture.

### Design consequences
- resistor values must be chosen from the intended pulse current
- brightness and supply current depend on both resistor choice and multiplex duty cycle
- resistor power and tolerance should be checked, even if the average dissipation is modest

## User input approach

### Decision
Version 1 includes one physical button for switching between preloaded animations.

### Reason
This gives the cube a simple standalone user interface without adding communication complexity or a larger control system.

### Design consequences
- one ESP32 GPIO must be reserved for the button input
- the input should use a defined idle state through an internal or external pull-up or pull-down
- firmware should debounce the button
- a short press can be used to step through animations in sequence

## Signal flow
The system signal flow is:

`ESP32 -> serial data / clock / latch -> driver chain -> column drive outputs -> LED column paths`  
`ESP32 -> serial data / clock / latch -> driver chain -> layer control outputs -> layer MOSFET gates -> active layer cathode to GND`  
`Button -> ESP32 GPIO -> animation selection logic`

The power flow is:

`USB-C 5 V input -> protection/filtering -> 5 V rail -> LED drive section`  
`USB-C 5 V input -> protection/filtering -> ESP32 5 V input -> onboard 3.3 V conversion`

## Power architecture

### 5 V rail
The 5 V rail is the main input rail. It powers:
- the LED drive path
- any driver ICs that require 5 V
- the ESP32 through its 5 V input path

### 3.3 V generation
The ESP32 receives 3.3 V from its own onboard 5 V to 3.3 V regulator or converter. Because of this, the controller PCB does not currently require a separate dedicated 3.3 V regulator stage for the ESP32.

### Protection and conditioning
The exact schematic implementation is still part of later work, but the architecture assumes:
- USB-C used as a 5 V input connector
- basic input protection and filtering
- bulk capacitance near the power entry
- local decoupling near controller and driver sections

## Firmware implications
This architecture requires firmware to separate three jobs:

### Refresh engine
- scans layers continuously
- updates one layer at a time
- loads both column-state data and layer-select data into the driver chain
- maintains stable refresh timing
- avoids flicker and visible instability

### Content engine
- stores voxel states in a framebuffer or equivalent structure
- converts animation patterns into 3D voxel data
- provides test patterns and preloaded effects

### Input and debug handling
- reads the animation-select button
- debounces the button input
- advances to the next animation when requested
- exposes simple serial debug output or commands

The refresh engine must run independently enough that animation updates and button handling do not disturb visual stability.

## PCB implications
This architecture creates several clear PCB priorities:

### Power routing
- active-layer current can be relatively high
- LED current paths must be short and appropriately sized
- return current paths should be obvious and low impedance

### Layer-switch routing
- MOSFETs should be placed so the layer current path is compact
- gate-drive traces from the driver chain should be clean and unambiguous
- current capability must be checked for worst-case active-layer load

### Driver placement
- the driver chain should be placed to support clean serial routing and short control paths
- the section controlling the MOSFET gates should be easy to trace and debug
- output grouping should make the layer-select logic obvious in both schematic and layout

### ESP32 placement
- keep power input and decoupling practical
- keep programming and debug access practical
- reserve a clean and convenient connection for the user button
- avoid introducing unnecessary routing complexity around the ESP32 board or module interface

### Noise and display integrity
- multiplexed current pulses can disturb logic if power routing is weak
- decoupling and grounding need to be considered early
- switching transitions should be controlled to reduce ghosting and instability

## What is included in Phase 2
This phase defines:
- display architecture
- low-side layer switching
- common-cathode layer arrangement
- driver-chain-based column control
- driver-chain-based layer MOSFET control
- 5 V USB-C power input
- ESP32 powered from its onboard 5 V to 3.3 V conversion path
- one button for animation switching
- firmware responsibilities at the architectural level

## Risks and engineering notes
- multiplexing reduces duty cycle, so brightness depends strongly on pulse current and refresh timing
- worst-case active-layer current must be calculated before selecting MOSFETs and connector strategy
- ghosting can appear if column data changes while a layer is still active
- the driver outputs used for MOSFET control must be checked to ensure reliable switching behavior
- power integrity is important because LED current pulses and ESP32 logic share the same board
- button handling must not interfere with the refresh timing
- the chosen architecture is intentionally simple and educational rather than optimized for maximum brightness or advanced grayscale control

## Conclusion
Version 1 uses an ESP32-controlled, multiplexed 8×8×8 monochrome LED cube architecture with a serial driver chain for both column control and layer selection, low-side MOSFET switching, common-cathode layers, USB-C 5 V power input, ESP32 onboard 5 V to 3.3 V conversion, and one button for switching between preloaded animations. This architecture is simple enough for a first custom controller PCB, fits the project’s documentation goals, and provides a solid base for schematic capture and PCB design.
